<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910812-0110</DOCNO><DOCID>910812-0110.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Most Investors Want   That Piece of Paper</HL><DATE>08/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11</SO><IN>CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Why are you so willing to consign stock certificates &quot;tothe graveyard&quot; (&quot;Stock Certificates Move a Step Closer to theScrap Pile,&quot; July 10) and abandon the rights of the retailinvestor?   The fact is, most retail investors do oppose theelimination of paper stock certificates and the establishmentof a computer (or &quot;book-entry-only&quot;) system. In astatistically valid survey of 750 confirmed stock-marketinvestors that we commissioned late last year, fully 81%agreed with that thought. Ironically, even among investorswho do not choose to hold their own stock certificates, 75%oppose book entry only.</LP><TEXT>   Those are the facts. The question is, why does Wall Streetinsist upon killing the golden goose -- the retail investor?   Morris Weissman   Chairman and CEO   United States Banknote Corp.   New York</TEXT></DOC>